How travel prices have evolved since 1989
Until 1989 there were only 5 state travel agencies in Czechoslovakia: Cedok, Sporturist, CKM, Rekrea and Autotourist.
Travel agencies at that time proposed trips especially in the countries of the Socialist bloc, as trips to the west were very limited.
Czech tourists traveled for holidays in East Germany, Soviet Union (Sochi, Crimea and Black Sea), Bulgaria, Romania (both in Black Sea) and Hungary (Balaton).
A great exception for the period from 1962 to 1972 when it was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia and then the regime began to have an inclination for the west and travel to Yugoslavia was very limited for Czech tourists.
The great paradox of the socialist era was that it was not allowed for the citizens of the socialist bloc (also for the Czechoslovakians) to travel individually even within the framework of the socialist countries.
If the Czechoslovak citizen wanted to travel individually, for example in Poland or in the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation, otherwise the individual trip was not allowed.
Travel agencies at that time also offered trips to the west, however, it was necessary to do the tail all night with a sleeping bag or to have a \"good knowledge\" within the travel agency.
And even after that it was not yet won.
The agreement for currencies that were the condition to travel west was denied to the politically incorrect people who could not travel at all.
However, the Czechoslovak currency was not interchangeable and it was not possible to obtain financial resources without the currency agreement (Western currency) to travel west.
The Czechs mostly spent their vacations in the country where there were therefore many cottages and cottages that the Czechs bought and this habit lasts until now.
The voyages of the Czechs have since 1989 experienced a great revolution.
Although until 1989 the holidays in East Germany and Bulgaria were at most, Czechs spent last year abroad 4 million days of holidays in countries around the world.
The great paradox we are not aware of today is that the most popular country is Croatia where it was not possible to go freely until 1989 because part of the Yugoslavia of the time.
The abolition of visas in the last century's 90's in the neighbouring countries of the west led to a huge wave of short-term visits, especially in Austria in Vienna and Germany.
Czechoslovakians could not travel by plane to the west for a long time that everyone wanted to see at least one moment.
For example, in Paris, travel organizations made Czechs sleep in tents in parks because our incomes did not allow us to pay the hotel or a pension.
The typical trait of a journey from Czechs was at that time to take with itself its own food preserves, sausages, etc... to save.
Another important moment was also the interchangeability of the Czech krona that finally allowed our tourists after dozens of years of freely buying Western currency.
Our standard of living and the average wage have increased, which has caused another important moment around 1997.
As a result of an increasing demand for travel, travel agencies have since 1997 begun to prepare tours with air charters that have significantly reduced costs compared to previous ones.
In the late 1990s, Czechs had visa-free connections with virtually most developed countries around the world apart from the EU that later facilitated our travels.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolution tourism, when the first air charter was prepared for an exotic country, Thailand, from the Czech Republic.
Since this year, as in each year, direct air charters have taken Czech tourists to the distant hot countries; this winter will have 12 exotic destinations from the Czech Republic.
More than 100,000 Czechs visit exotic countries every year!
Another interesting moment in this period that symbolizes our post-revolution development came in 2008.
On 17 November 2008, the EU abolished visas for Czech tourists and allowed our country to fully join the developed country group.
In 2008 also Czechs for the first time in history spent more than half of their holidays abroad (50.3%) and for the first time in history spent more than 15,000 crowns per person for holidays abroad, including attached charges. Crowns per person.
