MSS announces protocol to find the genes of obesity
Social Assurance leads an investigation to discover the genes of obesity in the case of children and young people; this is supported by experts from the IPN
The Mexican Institute of Social Insurance (IMSS) announced that it is conducting an investigation to discover the genes of obesity in the case of children and young people, called the 'Genetics of obesity of children and adolescents' protocol that will allow to have the markers associated with overweight.
In a press release, the head of the Medical Research Unit in Biochemistry of the Hospital des Specialités du Centre Médical National du 20e Sècle, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers had been formed.
This team is supported by specialists and graduate students from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Advanced Research and Study Centre (Cinvestav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
In the investigation, it is invited to participate in the population with or without the right, to attend the participating sports units of IMSS in Valle de México, where evidence is given to minors every Saturday from 8:00 a.m.
He stressed that the protocol began in the Kuauhtémoc Sport Unit (State of Mexico Poniente) and that from 8 October, the activity takes place in the Sports Unit of Nezahualcoyolt (State of Mexico Orient).
After reaching the goal of bringing 500 or 600 minors together, the study will continue in the Sports Independence Unit (south of Federal District) and finally in the Sports Unit Morelos (north of Federal District).
He explained that the objective of this investigation and that it is aware of the components and importance of genetics with regard to the development of obesity and to identify risk factors among Mexican children and young people in order to prevent the occurrence of chronic degenerative diseases.
As the World Diabetes Day will be celebrated on 14 November, he mentioned that the goal is to bring together three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years, with the consent and supervision of their parents, for the application of specific food-related questionnaires.
They will also be asked about their physical activity and history of family inheritance of their diseases, to avoid risk factors that trigger conditions such as diabetes or kidney failure.
It was detailed that Saturdays will be applied to all participants in anthropometric measurements (weight, size, circumference of size), blood pressure, determination of glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol and insulin and genetics (it is sought to identify people associated with childhood obesity).
Cruz López pointed out that this investigation is the result of the health professionals' concern about weight gain in the case of minors.
'The 1999 and 2006 health surveys reported that in just six years there has been a rise in the case of boys, 77 per cent in obesity and 47 per cent in girls; in the case of overweight, there has also been a dramatic increase', the IMSS specialist stressed.
He indicated that the rationale for finding markers is based on the fact that the population of the country is different from others from its genetic history.
He informed that, on average, Mexicans have 65 per cent indo-American heritage, 30 per cent in Europe and five per cent in Africa, and this condition is reflected in people associated with diabetes and overweight.
He explained that in general, the genetics of obesity translate into the inability to burn the excess energy that is consumed (calories), which is deposited in the form of fat.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit to participants is the full assessment of children, which allows them to detect whether they have a degree of overweight or obesity.
He even said that the presence of dark-colored pips (acanthosis) on the neck and forearms indicate the probability of suffering from metabolic and even prediabetic alterations.
The information is managed in a confidential way, doctors hand it in writing to parents, to whom it is explained each of the measures and changes in the lifestyle that they have to make in order to prevent disease.
Cruz López explained that there are three main components that cause overweight, obesity and other chronic conditions: sedentaryness, which is the lack of daily physical activity, stay most of the day sitting in front of the TV and use means of transportation instead of walking on short distances.
Another cause is the high caloric intake, i.e. the largest consumption of sugar drinks, carbohydrates (tamals - pasta from cornmeal wrapped in corn leaves -, bread, pizza, burgers, etc.) with a high content of fats and proteins and the genetic analyzed in this protocol.
UNAM's asphalt would avoid cashews
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the UNAM Faculty of Chemistry, develops modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with better performance, regardless of environmental and temperature conditions
If the signals that the pavement was resolved, it would no longer be necessary to repair approximately 200 thousand cases every rainy season in the Metropolitan Area of Valle de México, alert Rafael Herrera Nájera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of UNAM, which ensured that if the process of construction and maintenance of the bitumen pavement is adequate, the cases could be completely reduced or even eliminated.
During his conference A technological opinion on cassis, organized as part of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory responsible for developing modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture with similar characteristics to those of asphalt, but with greater mechanical resistance, both high and low temperatures.
Herrera Nájera felt that this type of modified asphalt could be used in places where the climate is extremely hot, such as some cities in the north of the country, to improve performance, and therefore the formation of cashews.
He explained that asphalt, the heaviest part of oil, is a set of hydrocarbon molecules, molecules with a heavier molecular weight, called asphaltenes, and molecules with a low molecular weight, called malthenes, which together give the paving its characteristic viscoelastic behaviour.
The viscoelastic behavior of the asphalt consists of the fact that at high temperatures, almost 180 degrees, it behaves as a liquid, at 120 degrees C its viscosity is very large and at 50 degrees C it has a very strong state, while at very low temperatures, the asphalt becomes breaking, it added.
This means that in the streets the asphalt resistance is not uniform and changes during the day according to environmental conditions and temperature, warns the chemical engineering specialist.
The FQ researcher observed that the majority of the streets of Mexico City were covered by a flexible pavement consisting of six layers of materials, the last three of which involve asphalt.
Among the more superficial layers is the asphalt layer, formed by small stones bathed in asphalt and subsequently compacted.
Each of the small stones that forms the layer, he reported, is bathed in asphalt.
When vehicles go through it by generating efforts, it allows the forces to spread very well in the pavement.
If we had modified asphalt, they would spread better, opined the chemical engineer.
On the asphalt layer, he said, one last layer is put called the rolling layer, made of fine stone, that is, of sand which is also bathed in asphalt.
As this is the layer in contact with the wheels of the vehicles, it must have more mechanical strength than the asphalt layer and provide adherence on the street.
Being the part of the pavement that receives and distributes efforts, the rolling stock also requires that it has an adequate thickness and the material it is made must be treated.
The climate, especially humidity and temperature variations, is also a very important factor to consider, especially water, he says, because they significantly affect the performance of the asphalt layer.
When the soil is wet, the water spreads inside the layer is difficult for it to sort, which softens all layers of the pavement and therefore causes the cassava.
In the process of formation of a case, he said, the first one that gets frustrated is the rolling film and only later is affected the layer of asphalt, but the damage does not take place immediately, but it is a process that must be treated to the first signals with adequate maintenance programs.
The member of the National Investigator System explained that the load of vehicles is another important factor for the formation of cassis and therefore the thickness of each layer of the pavement must always be linked to the load of vehicles and ensure its satisfaction, in order to avoid frequent formation of cashews.
