North Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The North Stream pipeline, directly connecting Western Europe to Russia through the bottom of the Baltic Sea, entered into service.
It must provide gas for the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, the Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate the event with bursts.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, participated last Tuesday on the shores of the Baltic, between the orchestra and the final buffet, at the inauguration of the North Stream, this new pipeline that directly connects Russia to Germany under the sea.
Symbolically, the German chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch counterpart Mark Rutte together turned the wheel of the valve commanding the entrance of Russian gas into the western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion cubic metres of additional Russian gas will arrive each year in Western Europe by a first 1,224 km tube connecting the St. Petersburg region to the Land of Mecklembourg-Pomerania.
A second tube must be completed at the end of 2012, allowing a total of 55 billion cubic metres of gas to be delivered, i.e. the equivalent of all French consumption.
And we already mention the possibility of building a third on the same course.
For Gazprom, the completion in time and time of this huge construction site has won airs.
The project had been strongly contested by Poland and the Baltic countries.
The North Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany, avoiding any land passage through a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
These two countries, in turn, lose a little of their power: it becomes more difficult for them to weigh on Russia by threatening to shut down access to western European markets.
At the height of the debate, Warsaw did not hesitate to compare North Stream to a new German-Soviet pact, in reference to the alliance between Hitler and Stalin to occupy Poland in 1939.
That is whether the issue is politically sensitive.
Western Europe, by supporting this Russian project, has gained greater security of its supplies.
But it is at the cost of a weakening of Europe's energy, as the project has created a gap between Eastern and Western Europeans.
Russia had only five years to triumph over its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which are heavily gas-consumer, and whose deposits are declining.
This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that binds us organically, and it has confirmed François Fillon by inaugurating this gas pipeline, demonstrating to what extent large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles displayed by the Gazprom leaders, present in number in Lubmin, at the point of arrival of the gas.
The construction of this pipeline is also a technical feat.
The submarine tube is made of concrete-boiled steel to protect it against the anchors of the ships.
It rests on the bottom of the sea, at 200 m on average.
To build it, it was necessary to avoid minefields dating from World War II.
A hundred have had to be removed or destroyed, with caution, by Jens Müller, spokesperson for North Stream.
It was also necessary to increase measures to protect wildlife and flora.
The tube is a long metal snake, heavy as 242 Eiffel towers, which nothing interrupts on its entire length: neither valve nor maintenance station.
A control platform was planned outside Sweden, but the project managers abandoned it while the Swedish people were reluctant to see a Russian State company established permanently off their coasts.
- In case of failure, we stop the gas passage in less than a minute - Jens Müller says.
In the event of a leak, the gas contained in the gas pipeline therefore escapes into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by manufacturers who have planned welds to experience a leak every 100,000 years.
The surveillance of the state of the gas pipeline is carried out by a submarine robot, driven by a ship, for external observation, as well as by a device that circulates inside the gas pipeline.
In the form of a cigar, it is introduced inside the tube, wide by a meter of diameter, and is pushed by the gas.
Upon arrival, after three full days of trip at the speed of 3 meters second, he delivers accurate information on the possible deformations of the metal.
The pipeline was designed to operate for fifty years without having to undergo any repairs.
The flow of gas is simply driven by pressure.
It is 200 bars from the start, and 100 bars from the finish.
Five companies have joined forces to carry out this project.
The leader remains Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
German E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as Dutch Gasunie and French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have set up a joint venture, named North Stream, which is responsible for building and operating the pipeline.
It has its headquarters in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased to this company, for twenty years renewable, the full capacity for gas transport.
“Gazprom will pay for total capacity, regardless of the amount of gas actually transported,” says Jens Müller.
Funding for the construction of the pipeline was provided to 30% by shareholders and 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of the work is expected to reach EUR 7.4 billion for both tubes.
For GDF Suez, for example, investment has risen to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure to return to their fees, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic to Lubmin, on a sandy coastline planted with pines.
Valves, 4.5 metres high, form the gas outlet door.
Sensors measure the pressure, temperature and specificities of the gas that happens before it is transferred to the German gas pipelines.
Since Tuesday, this terminal has been receiving a million cubic metres of Russian gas every hour.
At full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and in 2012, 6 million.
