Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain so high?
Approximately 19% of people with disabilities are looking for work.
The 15th week for the employment of disabled people is now open.
Despite a voluntary public policy set up in 2005, the unemployment rate of persons with disabilities is still twice as high as the average: 19%, compared with 9% for the entire population.
Discouraging?
No, says Éric Blanchet, Director General of Adapt, the association that organizes the week for the employment of the disabled.
- The progress made over the past 15 years is considerable. -
At the time, the unemployment rate was not two but three times higher.
“However, there is still a great deal to be done.”
It must be said that, for the disabled, obstacles remain many before accessing employment.
They are rather older: 37% are over 50 (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% do not have the bac and on the 2.3 million students in higher education, only 10,000 are disabled.
Finally, long-term unemployment is widespread: 53% for the disabled, compared with 38% on average.
In short, so many criteria that make the return to employment particularly difficult, and which - the core of the problem - are, according to Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association created in 1992 to help businesses recruit disabled workers.
This is for the objective brakes.
There remains the non-say, the attitudes that evolve, of course, but too slowly.
A study carried out in April by the IMS-Entrepreneur for the City indicated that the managers interviewed had a low level of knowledge of disability, with an over-representation of people in wheelchairs, psychic or intellectual deficits.
As a result, private enterprises with more than 20 employees are still far from reaching the employment target of 6% disabled workers, set out in a law of... 1987.
The last known figures from 2008 reported a ratio of 2.6%.
We are now around 3%, says Pierre Blanc, Chief Executive Officer of the Agency, the agency responsible for collecting contributions from companies that do not comply with this law.
The evidence: the number of establishments - taxed -, as well as the amounts paid, decreased between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 structures (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
The 2005 Act, which increased contributions, created a strong pressure on businesses, explains Pierre Blanc.
However, this improvement also translates into real awareness, especially in large groups.
According to the Ministry of Employment, only 59% of institutions from 20 to 49 employees employ disabled workers, compared with 82% of enterprises from 100 to 199 employees.
